\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 Caveats\
\pard\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
\pard\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf0 There are two things that you should be aware of when creating an environment file.\
\
1. Changes only take effect on the next login.\
\
2. \'91$value\'92 values do not expand like in a shell environment. So if you specify a environment variable HISTFILE with a value of \'91$HOME/.history\'92, you will not get \'91/somepath/to/user/.history\'92, you\'92ll get \'91$HOME/.history\'92.\
\
3. Changing the PATH variable is only advised if you know what you are doing. This variable can affect a variety of programs, including the developer tools, and shell environments.  For example, a user tried to set his path to \'91$PATH:/usr/local/bin\'92, not knowing about condition #2 above and found all of a sudden they could not compile anything or use Terminal.  So be careful.\
\
The application will notify you of these two latter issues (you can disable the warnings).  If you do find that applications are behaving strangely, remove the environment file or move it to a different name, and log out and back in again.\
\
\pard\partightenfactor0

